items.title: Local development 404 error
items.body:
```
Failed to load resource: the server responded with a status of 404 (Not Found) main.css
```

When the development server is running min.css is imported via style-loader therefore there is no need for the link during local development. Timkelty provides a interesting solution by adding the following code to his general.php file

```
// Hint to our templates if we're viewing through Neutrino/Webpack dev-server
'devServerProxy' => (bool) $_SERVER['HTTP_X_DEV_SERVER_PROXY'],
```

Perhaps there is a similar option to expose the devServerProxy variable using browserstack

items.title: GIMP recipe 404 error
items.body:
Just to report: the GIMP.download recipe is currently failing. Hopefully it’s a temporary issue. The recipe uses a file in https://download.gimp.org/pub/gimp/stable/ to determine the current version, but unfortunately the file is currently reporting 2.10.6, but the latest available for macOS is 2.10.4.

So, I don’t know whether it’s worth changing the recipe or just waiting for them to release 2.10.6 for Mac.

items.title: Improve 404 error
items.body:
Today I was using this gem and it returned 404 error for all my requests. I didn't know why. Only when I opened the raw_response, I saw that it has this body: ```html \n \n \n Error 404 Not Found\n \n

HTTP ERROR 404

\n

Problem accessing /solr/parts/parts/select. Reason:\n 

    Not Found

\n \n ``` We should be able to see exact 404 message, in this case: "

Problem accessing /solr/parts/parts/select. Reason:\n 

    Not Found
" Let's not work on it, if it's complex to do w/out an HTML parser

items.title: uwsgi deployment got 404 error.
items.body:
I got 404 when I try to connect to the socket from the client side.
This is the client side code, just like in the documentation:
```
<script type="text/javascript" src="//cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/socket.io/1.3.6/socket.io.min.js"></script>
<script type="text/javascript" charset="utf-8">
    var socket = io.connect('http://' + document.domain + ':' + location.port);
    socket.on('connect', function() {
        socket.emit('my event', {data: 'I\'m connected!'});
    });
</script>
```
And this is the uwsgi configuration file. 
```
[uwsgi]
if-env = VIRTUAL_ENV
virtualenv = %(_)
endif =

module = wsgi
master = true
processes = 5
http-websockets= true
http= :5000
gevent= 1000

die-on-term = true
```
